Yap, I missed that. Now I see the purpose of this class. I'm just thinking if we can somehow reuse already existent general functionality instead of introducing our own implementation and then support it.
I know we have #2033 but I don't see it to be resolved anytime soon. Thus, I think, in case we don't have better alternatives for some functionality, it's okay to use that functionality from Guava.
For example, Guava already has this concat functionality in Iterators. So, basically you would be able to do something like this:
public static <T> CloseableIterator<T> concat(final List<CloseableIterator<T>> iterators) {
    return Iterators.concat(iterators.iterator());
}

Instead of supporting this MultiIterator, but I see that MultiIterator not just concat iterators as Iterators.concat does, but also closes iterators which don't have any value anymore.
So, I was thinking, if it is right. I'm not sure yet. Maybe it is a correct implementation but for me it's a little bit confusing.
My confusion is that it's not clear, when exactly we trigger close for CloseableIterator. Looking in this PR I see that some Iterators automatically trigger close after the last element they read but some Iterators don't trigger this logic and expect external logic to trigger close for them (like LimitAdjustingIterator).
I need to look at this PR a little bit more deeply. I have a small feeling that we can remove our concat implementation and if each Iterator which implements CloseableIterator would close itself automatically, then we don't need to pass CloseableIterator iterator everywhere and we don't need to wrap Iterator as CloseableIterator when it doesn't have anything to close. That said, I could be completely wrong, I just didn't check the full PR yet.

